I"_<p>When you ask a large language model a question, it might feel like it‚Äôs ‚Äúthinking‚Äù or ‚Äúknowing things.‚Äù But what‚Äôs actually happening is much simpler and also more interesting!</p>

<p>An LLM doesn‚Äôt retrieve answers. <strong>It predicts the next token</strong>.</p>

<p>That‚Äôs it.</p>

<p>But this simple idea creates surprisingly complex behavior.</p>

<h2 id="the-core-idea-next-token-prediction">The Core Idea: Next Token Prediction</h2>

<p>At its core, a language model is trained to do one thing:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Given a sequence of words, predict the most likely next word.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>So if you type:
I drink coffee every</p>

<p>The model doesn‚Äôt ‚Äúknow‚Äù your habit. It calculates probabilities like:</p>

<ul>
  <li>morning ‚Üí 0.72</li>
  <li>day ‚Üí 0.18</li>
  <li>night ‚Üí 0.08</li>
</ul>

<p>Then it picks one (based on decoding rules like temperature or sampling).</p>

<p>This process repeats again and again until a full answer is formed.</p>

<h2 id="from-tokens-to-full-answers">From Tokens to Full Answers</h2>

<p>Let‚Äôs take a real example.</p>

<p>Prompt:
Explain why the sky is blue.</p>

<p>The model doesn‚Äôt jump to a full explanation.</p>

<p>It builds it step by step:</p>

<ol>
  <li>‚ÄúThe sky appears blue because‚Ä¶‚Äù</li>
  <li>‚Äúof the way sunlight‚Ä¶‚Äù</li>
  <li>‚Äúscatters in the atmosphere‚Ä¶‚Äù</li>
</ol>

<p>Each step is a new probability decision based on the previous text.</p>

<p>So the answer is not retrieved; it is constructed incrementally.</p>

<h2 id="where-understanding-comes-from">Where ‚ÄúUnderstanding‚Äù Comes From</h2>

<p>Even though it‚Äôs just predicting tokens, the model behaves like it understands concepts.</p>

<p>Why?</p>

<p>Because during training, it saw billions of examples where certain patterns repeat:</p>

<ul>
  <li>‚Äúsunlight ‚Üí scattering ‚Üí blue sky‚Äù</li>
  <li>‚Äúfever ‚Üí infection ‚Üí immune response‚Äù</li>
  <li>‚Äúif raining ‚Üí carry umbrella‚Äù</li>
</ul>

<p>It compresses all of this into statistical relationships inside its weights.</p>

<p>So when you ask a question, it‚Äôs not recalling facts; it‚Äôs activating patterns that <em>look like reasoning</em>.</p>

<h2 id="a-simple-intuition-example">A Simple Intuition Example</h2>

<p>Let‚Äôs simplify it.</p>

<p>Imagine a tiny dataset:</p>

<p>Q: What is 2 + 2?
A: 4</p>

<p>Q: What is 3 + 3?
A: 6</p>

<p>Q: What is 4 + 4?
A: ?</p>

<p>A human says: ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs 8 because addition pattern.‚Äù</p>

<p>A language model doesn‚Äôt ‚Äúunderstand addition‚Äù the way humans do.</p>

<p>Instead, it learns:</p>

<ul>
  <li>input pattern: ‚ÄúX + X‚Äù</li>
  <li>output pattern: ‚Äú2X‚Äù</li>
</ul>

<p>So it predicts ‚Äú8‚Äù because it fits the strongest learned pattern, not because it executes a symbolic rule.</p>

<h2 id="what-actually-controls-the-output">What Actually Controls the Output</h2>

<p>Even though probabilities exist, the final answer depends on decoding settings:</p>

<h3 id="temperature">Temperature</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Low temperature : more deterministic, safe answers</li>
  <li>High temperature : more diverse, creative answers</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="top-k--top-p">Top-k / Top-p</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Limits which candidate tokens are considered</li>
  <li>Helps avoid weird or low-probability outputs</li>
</ul>

<p>So the same prompt can produce slightly different answers depending on how sampling is configured.</p>

<h2 id="why-it-sometimes-gets-things-wrong">Why It Sometimes Gets Things Wrong</h2>

<p>Since everything is probability-based:</p>

<ul>
  <li>If similar patterns exist in training data ‚Üí strong answer</li>
  <li>If patterns are weak or conflicting ‚Üí hallucination risk</li>
</ul>

<p>The model will still produce <em>something fluent</em>, even if it‚Äôs incorrect.</p>

<p>Because fluency is optimized, not truth.</p>

<h2 id="a-useful-mental-model">A Useful Mental Model</h2>

<p>Instead of thinking:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>‚ÄúThe model knows the answer‚Äù</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Think:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>‚ÄúThe model is continuing text in the most statistically likely way based on everything it has seen.‚Äù</p>
</blockquote>

<p>That shift alone makes prompting much easier.</p>

<h2 id="why-prompting-actually-works">Why Prompting Actually Works</h2>

<p>Good prompts don‚Äôt ‚Äúask better questions.‚Äù</p>

<p>They:</p>

<ul>
  <li>shape the probability space</li>
  <li>reduce ambiguity</li>
  <li>activate the right patterns in training data</li>
</ul>

<p>So when you write a clear prompt, you are basically guiding the model toward a region of its learned distribution where the answer is more stable.</p>

<h2 id="final-thought">Final Thought</h2>

<p>LLMs are not reasoning engines in the human sense.</p>

<p>They are pattern engines that simulate reasoning extremely well.</p>

<p>And the surprising part is not that they sometimes fail, 
it‚Äôs that this simple mechanism works as well as it does.</p>
